>, probably Celtic (Gaulish) in origin but not firmly explained, which was Latinized as <i>Bricius</i>. It became popular in France through the cult of the 5th-century Saint Brice, successor of Saint Martin as Bishop of Tours, and was introduced to England and Scotland by the Normans. See also   Bryson  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Brys","meanings":["English (Lancashire): variant of   Bryce  ."]},{"name":"Bryson","meanings":["Scottish: patronymic from the personal name <i>Brice</i> + <i>-son</i> (see   Brice   and   Bryce  ).","Irish (Donegal): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Briosáin</b>, a form of <b>Ó Muirgheasáin</b> (see   Morrissey  ), altered by association with the Scottish surname <i>Bryson</i>, especially in Derry. <i>Bryson</i> was also used for   Breslin   in Donegal."]}]},{"name":"Henry","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Henry Bryce was born in 1425, in London, England, United Kingdom, his father, George Keble, was 10 and his mother, Mrs George Kebel, was 6. He married Alice de Radcliffe in 1450, in London, Middlesex, England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died on 19 June 1467, in his hometown, at the age of 42."},"et":{"1425–19 June 1467":"1425–19. juuni 1467","1425–1467":"1425–1467","1445–1517":"1445–1517","1430–1499":"1430–1499","1454–1482":"1454–1482","1415–1449":"1415–1449","1420–Female":"1420–Surnud","19 June 1467":"19. juuni 1467","1450":"1450","1482":"1482","1415":"